00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:19.550
And so one of the
things that I did

00:03:19.550 --> 00:03:23.872
was an interactive project
that was called "The Bored

00:03:23.872 --> 00:03:24.830
and Brilliant Project--

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:28.460
The Lost Art of Spacing
Out," and this was in 2015.

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:32.840
And the genesis of this was
actually that the podcast--

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:33.710
it was doing well.

00:03:33.710 --> 00:03:35.150
It was 2014.

00:03:35.150 --> 00:03:36.950
Podcasting was starting
to take off, which

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:38.280
was super exciting for me.

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:41.352
And I'd give us a
B-plus, A-minus.

00:03:41.352 --> 00:03:43.310
And I had this moment
where I was like, OK, how

00:03:43.310 --> 00:03:44.560
am I going to step up my game?

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:47.600
It was a cliched moment to have.

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:49.580
How am I going to come
up with better ideas?

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:51.140
And I had this
feeling like, well,

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:54.020
when was the last time that I
did come up with my best ideas?

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:55.370
And it was such a cliche.

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:57.980
It was like, oh, when
I'm driving in the car

00:03:57.980 --> 00:03:59.580
and staring out the window.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:02.300
I was never bored,
is what I realized.

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:04.460
I realized that all
the cracks in my day--

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:07.680
when I was waiting to get a
cup of coffee or I was waiting

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:09.680
to get on the subway
or to pick up my kids,

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:13.490
all those little moments
when I used to be spacing out

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:18.196
or thinking things through or
whatever, I now was looking--

00:04:18.196 --> 00:04:19.820
somebody did leave
their phone up here.

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:22.110
I was looking at this thing.

00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:24.080
And I guess I was like,
well, I guess never

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:27.107
being bored-- is
that a good thing?

00:04:27.107 --> 00:04:28.190
I guess it's a good thing.

00:04:28.190 --> 00:04:29.231
That's what they tell us.

00:04:29.231 --> 00:04:31.280
Only boring people
get bored, right?

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:33.260
But then I started
to wonder, well,

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.650
what actually happens in our
brains when we get bored?

00:04:36.650 --> 00:04:40.490
Or more importantly, what
could be happening to all of us

00:04:40.490 --> 00:04:42.560
if we never get
bored ever again,

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:46.520
if we don't experience this
human state that has, I think,

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:49.130
been with us for millennia?

00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:54.740
And so I reached out to my
listeners, and I was like,

00:04:54.740 --> 00:04:56.570
are you guys thinking
about this too?

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:59.240
Are you wondering how your
smartphones are changing

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:01.040
your thinking patterns?

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:03.470
Would you be interested
in maybe, I don't know,

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:04.940
doing a week of
experiments where

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:07.520
we see that if we changed
our smartphone habits how

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:09.350
it would affect our thinking?

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:11.570
And I thought a couple
hundred people would sign up

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:15.350
to play with me for a
week, and within 48 hours,

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:17.030
