00:06:02.277 --> 00:06:04.610
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: OK, so
[? Carin ?] and I, for one week

00:06:04.610 --> 00:06:06.740
in 2015-- every
morning we woke up,

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:08.270
and we put out a
little podcast that

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:11.600
explained the neuroscience of
what is going on in your brain

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:13.010
when you actually get bored.

00:06:13.010 --> 00:06:15.410
It describes some of
the technology's design,

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:17.960
in terms of getting our
attention and how we use it.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:19.970
And it asked them to do
a very small behavior

00:06:19.970 --> 00:06:22.550
change, something
to try that day just

00:06:22.550 --> 00:06:26.090
to see what would happen,
and then report back to us.

00:06:26.090 --> 00:06:27.840
And so, what we learned--

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:30.110
and I found that this
was fascinating-- we

00:06:30.110 --> 00:06:31.770
are at an extraordinary
moment when

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:35.280
it comes to understanding
what happens in the brain when

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:36.750
the mind wanders.

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:39.430
It's like-- it's really
hot news in neuroscience.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:41.520
So it turns out that
when you get bored,

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:45.610
you ignite a network in your
brain called the default mode.

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:48.960
And in the default mode, we
have our most original thoughts.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.970
We do our most
creative thinking.

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:53.500
We take two seemingly
disparate ideas,

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:56.160
we smash them together,
and create a new idea.

00:06:56.160 --> 00:06:58.860
And we do something that I
had never heard of before,

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:00.930
called autobiographical
planning.

00:07:00.930 --> 00:07:04.770
This is where you look
back at your earlier life

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:08.640
that you've had, and you take
note of the highs and the lows,

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:10.620
and you build a
personal narrative,

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:13.150
and then decide, you know, where
am I going to go from here?

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:14.100
What are my goals?

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:16.950
And you set the steps that
you need to reach those.

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:22.050
And so, kind of important stuff
that is going on in your brain.

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:24.660
And it also turns out
that a decade ago, we

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:28.249
shifted our attention at
work about every 3 minutes.

00:07:28.249 --> 00:07:29.790
And now, we're
shifting our attention

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:32.040
at work every 45 seconds.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:34.190
I found this amazing researcher.

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:35.850
Her name is Dr. Gloria Mark.

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:39.240
She's a professor of
informatics at UC Irvine.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:42.360
And she told me that the average
person is switching tasks

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:45.510
at work 566 times a day.

00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:47.730
So what I asked
Gloria was, I said,

00:07:47.730 --> 00:07:49.710
is it because the
technology has been

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:53.160
designed to take our attention
and get us switching like that?

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:54.990
Or is this just a
human thing that,

00:07:54.990 --> 00:07:57.120
if it wasn't the
technology, we'd

00:07:57.120 --> 00:07:59.290
be distracted by something else?

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:00.570
And here was her answer.

00:08:00.570 --> 00:08:02.820
GLORIA MARK: So I think
it's a combination.

00:08:02.820 --> 00:08:05.850
One thing that we found
is that there's actually

00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:09.450
physiological reasons that
can explain why people shift

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:11.530
their attention so rapidly.

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:15.030
So we find that when
people are stressed,

00:08:15.030 --> 00:08:17.850
they tend to shift their
attention more rapidly.

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:21.390
We also found, strangely
enough, the shorter amount

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:25.680
of sleep, that a person
gets, the more likely

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:27.040
they are to check Facebook.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.050
So we're in this
vicious habitual cycle.

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.299
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: I mean, I
thought that was hilarious

00:08:33.299 --> 00:08:35.250
and made complete
and utter sense,

00:08:35.250 --> 00:08:37.620
because when I am
tired at night,

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:40.980
that is when I find myself
going like this on my phone,

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:44.250
and not even looking at
whatever it is that I thought

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:45.150
I was looking for.

00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:48.090
And of course, I mean, I
think that has been a wake up

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:50.010
call for a lot of
Americans, this idea

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:52.890
that if the product is free,
then you are the product.

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:55.530
And we're seeing that
conversation be more and more

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:58.210
prevalent and more mainstream.

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:03.500
So really, the most
gratifying, I found,

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:05.930
was that a lot of classrooms
across the country

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:09.110
did the Bored and Brilliant
project, mostly high schools

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:11.850
and freshmen college kids.

00:09:11.850 --> 00:09:14.210
And here's how I
put it in the book.

00:09:14.210 --> 00:09:17.810
"Talking, listening,
eye contact, downtime,

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:20.480
responsiveness,
and yes, boredom,

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:23.240
are all activities that
now need to actively

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:25.010
be put into practice.

00:09:25.010 --> 00:09:27.740
It's not that digital
natives don't feel or know

00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:28.590
these things.

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:30.950
It's just that they
don't get prioritized.

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:34.370
And so, we must name,
schedule, and celebrate them,

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:36.320
whether it's the effect
that reading on screen

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.020
has on our attention
spans, or video game play

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:42.710
has on sociability, or
taking photos has on memory,

00:09:42.710 --> 00:09:45.500
we're living in an age
of self-experimentation.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:48.890
Technology is evolving faster
than researchers can study it.

00:09:48.890 --> 00:09:50.870
Science can't keep
up, which is why

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:53.990
we need a new interdisciplinary
approach, like the one we could

00:09:53.990 --> 00:09:55.790
offer with Bored and Brilliant.

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:58.760
Research now needs to
move out of the lab,

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:01.370
because life is the new lab."

00:10:01.370 --> 00:10:04.280
So just in case you think,
like, it's not a detox--

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:06.170
I absolutely refuse
to use that word,

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:07.980
because I don't
think it's a binary.

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:09.620
It's not on or off, right?

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:12.140
I think what we're
finding is that users need

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:14.240
to understand how it
fits into their lives

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:18.950
and turn their phones from what
have become task masters back

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:20.919
into tools that actually
improve their lives.

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:23.210
And right now, they're not
feeling like they're-- a lot

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:25.168
of them are feeling like
they're not there yet.

