them all off, all of them!

00:11:30.050 --> 00:11:32.330
OK, so people took all
kinds of things off.

00:11:32.330 --> 00:11:33.470
They took social media off.

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:34.670
They took games.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:37.790
Some people took news off,
if you've got a headline

00:11:37.790 --> 00:11:39.405
refreshing habit.

00:11:39.405 --> 00:11:41.030
But I will say, the
other thing that we

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:44.210
did during the original
project was that we partnered

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:46.550
with two different apps.

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:48.230
And I did get some
push-back on that.

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:49.813
People were like,
wait, you're telling

00:11:49.813 --> 00:11:52.890
us to download certain apps
in order to take apps off?

00:11:52.890 --> 00:11:55.440
I was like, look, we've got
to meet people where they are.

00:11:55.440 --> 00:11:57.820
So Moment was for the iPhone.

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:59.630
Break Free was for Android.

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:02.300
And what they did was measure
how many minutes a day

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:04.670
they were on their phone,
and how many pickups a day

00:12:04.670 --> 00:12:05.880
they were on their phone.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:08.330
So we were able
to have thousands

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:10.410
of people contributing
their data back to us.

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:12.170
And we were able
to measure which

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:14.600
days activities
were more effective

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:16.450
and which ones sort of were not.

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:19.730
So the first time around in
2015, I was totally winging it.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.522
I just made all
the experiments up.

00:12:22.522 --> 00:12:24.230
I was like, I don't
know, let's try this.

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:26.360
But what we were able to
do was go back and look

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.700
at all the data and the
stories, and codify it

00:12:28.700 --> 00:12:32.580
into what is now
the book, of course.

00:12:32.580 --> 00:12:36.020
So in the end, we had
20,000 people that one week,

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:37.530
all 50 states.

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:39.050
We measured that
90 percent of them

00:12:39.050 --> 00:12:41.802
cut down on their phone
time, which, you know,

00:12:41.802 --> 00:12:43.460
I kind of feel like,
OK, that's great.

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:44.960
But really, the
more important thing

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:48.170
was that 70 percent felt as
though they had more time

00:12:48.170 --> 00:12:51.580
to just think, which, I mean--

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.680
I just did a TED talk, and
they were like, I don't know,

00:12:54.680 --> 00:12:56.930
is that going to be enough
that, like, your message is

00:12:56.930 --> 00:12:58.470
that people need to think?

00:12:58.470 --> 00:12:59.900
I was like, shocking, right?

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:02.590
Liam got back in
touch two weeks ago,

00:13:02.590 --> 00:13:04.340
because I did a shout
out to my listeners.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:06.560
