never heard of it at all,

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:06.891
but this is something that's
sort of been on their mind

00:16:06.891 --> 00:16:08.660
and they want to explore.

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:11.920
So I'm going around the country.

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:13.340
And I'm having lots of fun.

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:15.760
And I'm making people take
selfies, because as I said,

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:18.750
this is not an all or
nothing sort of thing.

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:20.380
There are moms
going out drinking

00:16:20.380 --> 00:16:23.299
before they come to hang out
with me, which has been great.

00:16:23.299 --> 00:16:25.090
And I thought this
review was really funny,

00:16:25.090 --> 00:16:26.920
that "This could do
for unplugging what

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:29.950
Marie Kondo's 'The Life
Changing Magic of Tidying Up'

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:32.337
did for decluttering."

00:16:32.337 --> 00:16:33.170
I mean, I love that.

00:16:33.170 --> 00:16:35.500
That would be great, if I
was as big as Marie Kondo.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.350
But to me, what's more
interesting is really,

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.660
since I finished
writing this book,

00:16:40.660 --> 00:16:42.230
a lot has changed
in this country.

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:45.610
It is really hard not
to continually refresh

00:16:45.610 --> 00:16:47.770
the headlines, or Twitter.

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:49.900
Just ask the president.

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:51.760
But I think perhaps
it's time for us

00:16:51.760 --> 00:16:54.970
to collectively rethink
some of our tech habits,

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:56.470
because the other
thing that happens

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:59.950
when you ignite the default
mode is you do empathy.

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:02.620
You imagine what other people
around you are thinking,

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:03.910
and how they're feeling.

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:06.430
And if there is one thing this
country could use right now,

00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:09.970
is a little empathy, and
some creative problem solving

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:15.589
to sort of find solutions to
some huge economic, racial,

00:17:15.589 --> 00:17:16.880
and environmental issues.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:19.690
And so, I think particularly
for young people

00:17:19.690 --> 00:17:25.510
to understand that quickness
isn't necessarily a virtue,

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:28.930
or as the Exchequer of
the Bank of England said,

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:31.940
he's worried that quick thinking
could make for slow growth.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:36.410
So this is not just a, you
know, self-help-y sort of thing,

00:17:36.410 --> 00:17:38.110
but I think, really,
an economic thing,

00:17:38.110 --> 00:17:39.970
that we need people
to take a minute

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:44.560
and let a mediocre idea that
they might want to share just

00:17:44.560 --> 00:17:46.700
sit on it for a little while.

00:17:46.700 --> 00:17:48.380
Let it turn into
something bigger.

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:51.640
Let it turn into a big solution,
which a lot of young people

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:54.110
are not used to doing.

00:17:54.110 --> 00:17:57.560
So I'm just telling
people to get bored.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.440
That's all I want them to
do, on this big book tour

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:02.070
that I'm on right now.

00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:04.679
And you heard about the podcast.

00:18:04.679 --> 00:18:06.470
You've heard about my
listeners experience,

00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:08.469
some of the new people
that I'm meeting.

00:18:08.469 --> 00:18:10.010
And I would love to
talk to you guys,

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:12.020
because you're the
first tech company

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:14.190
that I've gone to to
make this presentation.

00:18:14.190 --> 00:18:17.510
So I would love to hear,
like, what your thoughts are

00:18:17.510 --> 00:18:22.220
on this, your comments, any
questions, personal experience.

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:23.060
That would be great.

00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:26.020
And thank you for having me.

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:26.700
RODNEY: Great.

