AUDIENCE: So I guess my
question was, do you do--

00:26:48.070 --> 00:26:49.720
in the course of
writing the book,

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:52.680
did you find that meditation
also helped with this,

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:54.492
with increasing
creativity and kind of--

00:26:54.492 --> 00:26:55.450
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: Yeah.

00:26:55.450 --> 00:26:57.575
AUDIENCE: --putting life
on pause for a little bit?

00:26:57.575 --> 00:26:59.320
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: It's
a different thing.

00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:01.760
Meditation ignites a
different part of the brain.

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:04.630
It is completely different
than the mind wandering part.

00:27:04.630 --> 00:27:09.800
So the mind wandering thing
is when you are doing nothing.

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:13.960
So it could be, like,
repetitive folding of laundry,

00:27:13.960 --> 00:27:15.880
or it could be walking
to work, or something

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:18.647
that doesn't require active
focus on what you're doing.

00:27:18.647 --> 00:27:20.230
The idea with
meditation is that there

00:27:20.230 --> 00:27:22.930
is active focus on thinking
about nothing, right,

00:27:22.930 --> 00:27:24.550
or the clearing of the mind.

00:27:24.550 --> 00:27:26.030
That is what you are focused on.

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:27.310
And so that is its own thing.

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:29.830
But this is truly letting--

00:27:29.830 --> 00:27:32.410
the mind wandering part
goes into daydreaming.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:34.370
And it can also go
to some bad places.

00:27:34.370 --> 00:27:35.639
I mean, let's make no mistake.

00:27:35.639 --> 00:27:37.180
Just because you
let your mind wander

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:40.600
doesn't mean like, holy shit,
you have the next great startup

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:41.490
idea, right?

00:27:41.490 --> 00:27:45.220
There's dysphoric
thinking, which

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:48.460
is a rumination, which is
going to be me tomorrow,

00:27:48.460 --> 00:27:51.370
going over this talk, and how
some of the PowerPoint slides

00:27:51.370 --> 00:27:54.409
fired themselves, and how much
that annoyed me, and thinking,

00:27:54.409 --> 00:27:56.200
you know, if only I
could go back to Google

00:27:56.200 --> 00:27:57.460
and give that talk
over-- you know,

00:27:57.460 --> 00:27:59.126
I'm going to be
