00:29:15.580 --> 00:29:18.680
So I'm curious, I guess, what
is the sort of definition

00:29:18.680 --> 00:29:19.350
of boredom?

00:29:19.350 --> 00:29:20.891
So, like, for example,
the experience

00:29:20.891 --> 00:29:22.917
of walking down a nice
trail is very different

00:29:22.917 --> 00:29:24.292
from the experience
of, you know,

00:29:24.292 --> 00:29:25.380
walking down New York City--

00:29:25.380 --> 00:29:25.635
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: Yes.

00:29:25.635 --> 00:29:27.250
AUDIENCE: --or even running
versus walking, I feel,

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:28.020
are kind of different.

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:30.519
So I'm curious if there's sort
of activities or environments

00:29:30.519 --> 00:29:33.300
that are more boring than
others, or if it matters?

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:35.400
MANOUSH ZOMORODI: So I
got a lot of push-back

00:29:35.400 --> 00:29:38.229
when I first used the
word boredom on the show.

00:29:38.229 --> 00:29:40.770
People were like, could you call
it something a little nicer,

00:29:40.770 --> 00:29:43.120
please, like daydreaming?

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:47.730
And I was like, no, actually,
boredom is the perfect word,

00:29:47.730 --> 00:29:50.010
because I think that is
really what we're seeing,

00:29:50.010 --> 00:29:52.470
is that why do we
distract ourselves?

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:54.670
Because we feel uncomfortable.

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:57.060
And if you look at the
history of boredom,

00:29:57.060 --> 00:29:59.760
I mean, there's a really
nerdy chapter on that, too,

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:03.510
which is that the word
didn't appear until 1853.

00:30:03.510 --> 00:30:05.950
Charles Dicken's
"Bleak House," boredom.

00:30:05.950 --> 00:30:07.110
And it makes sense, right?

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:10.440
Industrial Revolution,
people have more free time.

00:30:10.440 --> 00:30:12.330
They have time to be bored.

00:30:12.330 --> 00:30:14.040
But if you look
back even further,

00:30:14.040 --> 00:30:16.950
Kierkegaard preferred
the word idle.

00:30:16.950 --> 00:30:18.210
The French called it ennui.

00:30:21.062 --> 00:30:22.770
I'm thinking of other
philosophers who've

00:30:22.770 --> 00:30:25.110
describe it as this sort
of existential angst

00:30:25.110 --> 00:30:27.630
that we have-- what is
my purpose here on earth,

00:30:27.630 --> 00:30:29.830
Heidegger in particular.

00:30:29.830 --> 00:30:32.310
So for me, using
the word bored--

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:34.920
I think there are
those of us who

00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:37.685
find mind wandering
wonderful, or maybe we

00:30:37.685 --> 00:30:40.060
used to think it was boring,
but now we think it's great.

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:42.060
I think parents, in
particular, who never have

00:30:42.060 --> 00:30:45.000
time to get bored, like it.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:47.910
But I really specifically wanted
to use that word because I

00:30:47.910 --> 00:30:51.120
think some people-- particularly
I see this with young people--

00:30:51.120 --> 00:30:52.500
think that they
can skip straight

00:30:52.500 --> 00:30:55.056
to the good original
thinking stuff, that like,

00:30:55.056 --> 00:30:56.680
an apple's going to
drop on their head,

00:30:56.680 --> 00:30:58.304
and they're going to
have a great idea.

00:30:58.304 --> 00:31:01.340
And I feel like,
no, actually, you're

00:31:01.340 --> 00:31:02.590
going to-- it's going to hurt.

00:31:02.590 --> 00:31:03.940
It's going to be painful.

00:31:03.940 --> 00:31:07.590
It's going to suck until
the good stuff comes.

00:31:07.590 --> 00:31:09.210
I gave the book
earlier this summer

00:31:09.210 --> 00:31:13.530
to a chemistry major, a
student at American University,

00:31:13.530 --> 00:31:16.020
and had him record
his experience.

00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:17.814
And you hear him just
like, oh my god, I

00:31:17.814 --> 00:31:18.730
don't want to do this.

00:31:18.730 --> 00:31:21.540
I really don't want to do
this-- just really struggling.

00:31:21.540 --> 00:31:23.430
I don't recognize this feeling.

00:31:23.430 --> 00:31:25.140
Normally, I would
just look at my phone

00:31:25.140 --> 00:31:27.000
whenever I have these feelings.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.940
And then you get
to like, Day Five.

00:31:29.940 --> 00:31:33.060
And he goes for this
walk in Rock Creek Park.

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:35.440
And he's like, I'm
just going to do it.

00:31:35.440 --> 00:31:38.670
I'm just going to, you know,
succumb to the mind wandering.

00:31:38.670 --> 00:31:41.640
And he comes up with
this amazing idea

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:44.880
related to solar
panels and the hometown

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:47.340
that he grew up in,
in Puerto Rico, which

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:49.950
has a disproportionate
amount of churches

00:31:49.950 --> 00:31:53.010
that have a lot of roof,
square footage, that could be--

00:31:53.010 --> 00:31:55.380
I mean, he just goes off
on this crazy tangent.

00:31:55.380 --> 00:31:58.170
And like, we kind
of heard, like,

00:31:58.170 --> 00:31:59.940
an epiphany happening on there.

00:31:59.940 --> 00:32:03.300
So I think
particularly teenagers

00:32:03.300 --> 00:32:04.890
said to me when
they did it, like,

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:06.370
oh, I don't like this feeling.

00:32:06.370 --> 00:32:07.920
I don't recognize it.

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:09.690
I was like, yeah,
that's boredom.

00:32:09.690 --> 00:32:11.940
So just like, stick with it.

00:32:11.940 --> 00:32:14.060
Lean into it.

00:32:14.060 --> 00:32:17.660
But it's however you
kind of define it.

00:32:17.660 --> 00:32:22.460
It's as personalized as your
home screen, I would say.

